        {
          "criterion": "Continuous improvement / commendation",
          "rawCriterion": "Summary / recommendation",
          "tone": "strength",
          "comment": "The class is scheduled 12:45-2:35. I was there from 12:45 until 1:55. The students are designing a college advising system. Most students are working by themselves but two students are working as a group. At the beginning of class, Kenny had the students sit in a circle. He asked each student in turn to describe what he had done lately for his project. The first student said he reviewed the College’s advising system and considered what needs to be improved. He said he is getting familiar with the program. He hasn’t gotten much information about registration, but he will talk to people in the One Stop to get some information. The next two students, working together on the same project, are in the process of doing a survey of students and advisors. So far, they have found that the majority of the students they have talked to, about 80%, are not happy with the registration system. They said there is not enough help and not enough notifications that announce when payments are due. They have not talked to many advisors yet, but they have found out that it can be frustrating for advisors to set up class schedules with advisees. There are some flaws in the system. Kenny asked the students to elaborate on the frustrations of the advisors. There is a time concern, that students don’t always have time to come in to see their advisors. Students can’t always find faculty outside their major to ask questions about classes outside their major. And their advisors can’t always advise properly for classes not in their area. The third student wants to define what an advising and registration system is. He identified the steps that are taken for registration. He wants to do a competitor analysis. He will recommend a new system, and define what he likes and what he doesn’t like. The fourth student wants to create an application and update it. She will get information from questionnaires. She said that with the current system, people have problems getting all the information they need, and also students have trouble scheduling a meeting with their advisors. After the students talked about what they had accomplished so far, Kenny had the students interview Kenny and me about advising. The students knew about this ahead of time and had prepared questions. Kenny pointed out that the roles of the advisee and advisor should be clearly defined in the system. The students asked about what we didn’t like. I mentioned some technical issues, like the Add boxes are missing the first time you grant permission for an advisee to register. I always have to log out and go back in and then the Add boxes are there. Kenny suggested that I just hit the Refresh instead. I also mentioned that the system can’t handle multiple prerequisites for the same course. In that case, a person other than the faculty advisor has to add the course to the student’s schedule. Kenny mentioned that some improvements should make the system more flexible to handle all requests. He also said that it should be easier to find more information; for example, there should be a drop-down menu for each Gen. Ed. category in the system, and also each subject area prefix, like SCI. You should be able to click on a course on this menu to add it to the course schedule for the advisee. So that advisees know what they are responsible for, there should be a preparation checklist, where the advisees could do the things on the list and check them off to get ready for their meeting with their advisor. The advisee could do more steps independently first, and the advisor could check what the advisee has done. For example, one thing could be to look at the course list ahead of time and pick some courses that fit into categories on the tracksheet. Kenny thinks the tracksheet could automatically update when a course is chosen from a list. Kenny told the students that he thinks the system should be more robust and not allow mistakes to happen. Kenny wants current information in the system, not outdated information. A current tracksheet should be available in the system. One student asked what notifications the faculty would want, and Kenny said he did not want any notifications from the system. The student said that students would want notification about holds, so they can clear up the holds before it is time to register for classes. Kenny said that New Paltz gives each student a set registration time, and a checklist of what the student has to do before registering. One student mentioned that even though he had a payment plan set up, the system would not let him register. The student called the college, and nobody answered. He waited for hours and could not get in touch with anybody by phone, so he ended up having to come to campus just to deal with this problem. Another problem is that sometimes a course taught by TBA does not even have a time listed at first. Kenny thinks it is a good idea for an advisee and advisor to map out not just the next semester, but all future semesters. There should be a place in the system to do this. One student said that he had to keep going back and forth from a person in the One Stop to doing some procedures online. She should be able to see only one person, not run around back and forth to get everything done for registration. Another example of a necessary feature is that the system should not allow a student to register for a lower level math when the student has already taken a higher level in the sequence. A student said that he was placed into Intermediate Algebra once he got to the College even though he had taken Precalculus for college credit in high school. This was an excellent class since the students were discussing issues that they noticed in a real computer software product, and figuring out ways it could be improved. Having the time to talk over issues with both Kenny and other classmates was very helpful to the students, I’m sure."
        }
