          "criterion": "Continuous improvement / commendation",
          "rawCriterion": "Summary / recommendation",
          "tone": "strength",
          "comment": "to 10:45. There are 7 students enrolled in the class; 4 of them were present. At the beginning of class, students were at seats in front of computers, but they were facing toward the inside of the classroom, kind of like in a circle. Kenny had a conversation with each student in turn about his or her individual project. The students had chosen their topics already, and were reporting to Kenny the progress they had made on their projects so far. Kenny asked the students questions about the steps they were taking and what their options are. He gave them some suggestions about next steps and resources. He said they first have to design and then start implementing. One student said she did some research on what features she wanted to have in her weather app. One student wanted to learn how to use React, a language he did not know yet. Kenny told the students they will be graded on process rather than on the final product. He told the students they should first sketch what they want, then program what they have sketched. He said a lot of the tools that they can use are open source. I noticed that the students were using their own computers rather than the computers in the room. This is so they can work on the same things at home and on campus, and they can access what they need wherever they are. Kenny said I could look at each student’s work and ask questions. The first student was working on her weather app. She wants to be able to get data from weather sites on demand at the users’ desired locations. The next student was working on a recipe app. He wants it to be easy to use, one page, short, and he doesn’t want the user to have to sign in. The third student was doing a To Do List app. The student told me he wants to make it so that when the user does something on the list, it gets checked off or crossed out. He said the user can have multiple To Do Lists on the app. The 4th student was also doing a To Do List app, but he was working on a table for it where the blocks were different colors. While I was there, all the students were working independently and did not ask Kenny for any help, but he was right there and available to help them. I think this way of teaching computer skills is the best way since the students are learning independently as much as possible and they have access to individual help from Kenny throughout the class. The students can pick topics based on their own interests, which will help them be successful since they will be more willing to put effort into something they are really interested in. Kenny is very encouraging and helpful to the students, but he lets them do as much as possible on their own. I don’t have any recommendations for improvement."
